#compdef eta
# =============================================================================
# eta — the Eta programming language compiler.  Eta is a STRONGLY TYPED
#       PURELY FUNCTIONAL dialect of HASKELL targeting the JAVA VIRTUAL
#       MACHINE (JVM).  Written in Haskell as a hard fork of GHC 7.10.3,
#       Eta compiles Haskell source code to .class files that run on
#       any JVM 1.7+ and interoperate with the entire Java ecosystem
#       via Eta's Foreign Function Interface (FFI) for Java.  Created
#       by Rahul Muttineni and TypeLead in 2016-2017 as a commercial
#       successor to Frege (the other Haskell-on-JVM project).  Where
#       Frege is academically-aimed and JNI-shy, Eta was designed as a
#       PRODUCTION-READY JVM Haskell with seamless Java interop, lazy
#       evaluation, type classes, and the full GHC Haskell 2010 +
#       extensions feature set.  Used at TypeLead's client engagements
#       in finance / fintech before TypeLead pivoted to commercial-only
#       offerings around 2020; the open-source compiler remains available
#       for research, education, and legacy migrations.
#
# Author:  TypeLead (Rahul Muttineni, Jyothsna Patnam, Joel Stanley, et al.)
#          — Bangalore-based PL research company that built Eta as their
#          first commercial Haskell-on-JVM product
# Source:  https://github.com/typelead/eta
# CLI:     eta/Main.hs + compiler/Eta/Main/CmdLineParser.hs
#          (uses GHC's CmdLineParser inherited from Glasgow Haskell
#          Compiler — hard-forked from GHC 7.10.3's parsing infrastructure)
# Library: Eta.Main.CmdLineParser (forked from GHC's
#          `compiler/main/CmdLineParser.hs`)
#          ("Abstract command-line parser used by both StaticFlags and
#           DynFlags — the GHC-Haskell CLI library that inherits all
#           of GHC's flag-parsing sophistication into the Eta compiler")
# License: BSD-3-Clause + Apache-2.0 (Eta runtime libs)
# Status:  ARCHIVED — TypeLead pivoted to commercial-only offerings ~2020;
#          eta/typelead repo last meaningfully updated 2019.  2629+ stars.
#          The Eta language compiler is research-quality but not
#          production-recommended today (Frege remains the actively-
#          maintained Haskell-on-JVM alternative).  This completion
#          documents Eta as the canonical embodiment of GHC's
#          sophisticated CmdLineParser CLI library applied to a non-
#          GHC binary.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 63RD DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its 63RD LANGUAGE (Eta, via the eta compiler binary).  Eta joins the
# taxonomy as the FIRST GHC-hard-fork language whose CLI library is
# GHC's CmdLineParser — the most sophisticated documented CLI library
# variant in terms of OptKind variants (12 distinct flag-shape
# constructors), monadic parser-state (the EwM "errors-and-warnings
# monad"), and four-tier flag-mode taxonomy (OnlyGhc / OnlyGhci /
# AllModes / HiddenFlag).  New language tally: 63.  Top-language
# tally remains Rust=37 / Go=37 / TS-Node=37 (THREE-WAY TIE).  Taxonomy
# now spans 260 cross-language CLI library variants across 63 documented
# languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS GHC'S CmdLineParser AND WHY IS IT THE 63RD LANGUAGE'S ENTRY?
#
# Eta's CLI is **GHC's CmdLineParser** (from Glasgow Haskell Compiler),
# hard-forked into `compiler/Eta/Main/CmdLineParser.hs`.  This is a
# distinct CLI library variant in the cross-language taxonomy because:
#
#   1. It's NOT a parser meant for general Haskell programs to use —
#      this is the SPECIFIC parser GHC built for ITS OWN compiler-flag
#      surface (with hundreds of flags spanning warning controls, language
#      extensions, optimization passes, target codegen, runtime tuning,
#      interactive-mode features, etc.).
#   2. It exposes a deeply algebraic option-kind taxonomy via the
#      `OptKind m` sum type with TWELVE constructors covering every
#      flag-shape variation needed to describe GHC's surface.
#   3. It's wrapped in an `EwM` monad transformer ("errors-and-warnings
#      monad") that accumulates parse-time diagnostics WITHOUT short-
#      circuiting — letting the parser report ALL errors + warnings in
#      a single pass rather than the first one.
#   4. It uses four flag-mode tiers (OnlyGhc | OnlyGhci | AllModes |
#      HiddenFlag) to scope which flags are accepted in which compiler
#      mode (batch compilation vs. interactive REPL vs. shared vs.
#      hidden from --help).
#
# Eta inherits ALL of this from GHC and uses it for the eta compiler's
# flag surface (Haskell language extensions, JVM target options,
# warning controls, etc.).  Documenting Eta also documents GHC's
# CmdLineParser-style CLI library by extension.
#
# GHC CmdLineParser is DISTINCT from every documented CLI library on
# SEVEN specific axes:
#
#   1. TWELVE-CONSTRUCTOR `OptKind m` SUM TYPE — the richest flag-shape
#      taxonomy of any documented CLI library:
#         data OptKind m
#             = NoArg     (EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -f all by itself
#             | HasArg    (String -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -farg or -f arg
#             | SepArg    (String -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -f arg (separator REQUIRED)
#             | Prefix    (String -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -farg attached
#             | OptPrefix (String -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -f OR -farg (optional value)
#             | OptIntSuffix (Maybe Int -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -f or -f=n; pass n
#             | IntSuffix (Int -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -f=n; pass int
#             | FloatSuffix (Float -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -f=n; pass float
#             | PassFlag  (String -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -f; pass "-f" to fn
#             | AnySuffix (String -> EwM m ())
#                 -- e.g. -f or -farg; pass entire "-farg"
#             | PrefixPred    (String -> Bool) (String -> EwM m ())
#                 -- predicate-matched prefix
#             | AnySuffixPred (String -> Bool) (String -> EwM m ())
#                 -- predicate-matched suffix
#      Compare:
#        getopt (POSIX C):     NO_ARGUMENT / REQUIRED_ARGUMENT /
#                              OPTIONAL_ARGUMENT — three kinds
#        argp (GNU):           ARG_OPTIONAL flag + three kinds — four total
#        Nemerle CliOption R505: 9 variants (Flag/Boolean/String/Int/
#                              NonOption/Unhandled/SubstitutionString/
#                              PreHelp/PostHelp) — second-richest
#        Cone opt_arg R517:    3 kinds (NONE / REQUIRED / OPTIONAL)
#        Virgil BasicOptions R501: generic Option<T> with onSet — single
#                              parameterized type
#        clap (Rust):          rich num_args spectrum but not 12
#                              distinct constructors
#        GHC CmdLineParser:    TWELVE constructors covering every
#                              imaginable flag-shape — UNIQUE
#                              comprehensiveness.
#      The 12-constructor design lets GHC describe flags like:
#        -O3        (Prefix)
#        -Wall      (Prefix)
#        -fno-warn-orphans (AnySuffix)
#        -dverbose-core2core (Prefix)
#        -fmax-inline-rhs-size=12 (IntSuffix)
#        -funfolding-creation-threshold=750 (IntSuffix)
#        -hide-package=text (PrefixPred + value)
#      all using DIFFERENT OptKind constructors that capture the
#      shape-specific parsing logic.
#
#   2. `EwM` MONAD TRANSFORMER ("ERRORS AND WARNINGS MONAD") — GHC's
#      parser runs INSIDE a monad transformer that ACCUMULATES errors
#      and warnings without short-circuiting:
#         newtype EwM m a = EwM { unEwM :: Located String
#                                       -> Errs -> Warns
#                                       -> m (Errs, Warns, a) }
#         addErr  :: Monad m => String -> EwM m ()
#         addWarn :: Monad m => String -> EwM m ()
#         deprecate :: Monad m => String -> EwM m ()
#      Each flag handler runs `addErr` / `addWarn` / `deprecate` to
#      record diagnostics; the parser collects ALL diagnostics from
#      ALL flags and reports them together at the end.  Compare:
#        argparse (Py):    raises on first error; no monadic
#                          accumulation
#        clap (Rust):      `Result<T, Error>` — first-error short-circuit
#        cobra (Go):       returns single error
#        cmdliner (OCaml): Term values compose but errors short-circuit
#        GHC CmdLineParser: MONADIC error-accumulation — UNIQUE.
#      Enables GHC to report all flag errors at once: `eta -fno-warn-foo
#      -O5 -unknown-flag` reports all three issues in one error message
#      rather than three sequential failures.
#
#   3. FOUR-TIER `GhcFlagMode` FLAG SCOPING — flags can be tagged with
#      one of four modes:
#         data GhcFlagMode
#             = OnlyGhc    -- only in non-interactive (batch) mode
#             | OnlyGhci   -- only in interactive (REPL) mode
#             | AllModes   -- both modes
#             | HiddenFlag -- accepted but hidden from --help / completions
#         defFlag    name optKind = Flag name optKind AllModes
#         defGhcFlag name optKind = Flag name optKind OnlyGhc
#         defGhciFlag name optKind = Flag name optKind OnlyGhci
#         defHiddenFlag name optKind = Flag name optKind HiddenFlag
#      Compare:
#        argparse (Py):    --help text is a single string per option
#                          (you can hide with `help=SUPPRESS`)
#        clap (Rust):      `#[arg(hide = true)]` for hidden flags;
#                          no mode-scoping
#        cobra (Go):       `cmd.Hidden = true` + group annotations
#        Nemerle (R505):   NOHELP string sentinel for hidden flags
#        GHC CmdLineParser: FOUR-TIER mode scoping built into the
#                          flag-record type — UNIQUE.
#      This is essential for GHC because the same binary has BATCH
#      mode (`ghc Foo.hs`) and INTERACTIVE mode (`ghci`), and many
#      flags are mode-specific.  Eta inherits this for `eta` (batch)
#      vs `eta repl` (interactive).
#
#   4. THREE-PASS PARSING (static / mode / dynamic) — Eta/GHC's main()
#      drives a THREE-PHASE PARSE:
#         (argv2, staticFlagWarnings) <- parseStaticFlags argv1
#           -- Phase 1: extract STATIC flags that affect runtime
#           --          initialization (-B, library paths, etc.)
#         (mode, argv3, modeFlagWarnings) <- parseModeFlags argv2
#           -- Phase 2: extract MODE flags (--make, --interactive,
#           --          --help, --version, --depend, --print-* etc.)
#         (dflags, argv4, dynFlagWarnings) <- parseDynamicFlags
#                                                 dflags0 argv3
#           -- Phase 3: parse remaining flags as DYNAMIC compiler
#           --          flags (language extensions, optimization
#           --          levels, warning controls)
#      Compare:
#        Most CLI libraries:  single-pass parsing
#        GHC CmdLineParser:   THREE-PASS — static / mode / dynamic
#                             phases each consume their own flag subset
#                             and leave the rest for the next phase.
#      Reflects GHC's complexity: some flags affect the COMPILER
#      INITIALIZATION (need to be processed before the compiler is
#      even constructed), some affect the MODE (compile vs. interpret
#      vs. depend vs. print), and most affect dynamic compilation
#      behavior (per-file overridable).
#
#   5. `CmdLineP` STATE-PASSING MONAD — flag handlers can MODIFY
#      compiler state via the `CmdLineP` monad:
#         newtype CmdLineP s a = CmdLineP { runCmdLineP :: s -> (a, s) }
#         getCmdLineState :: CmdLineP s s
#         putCmdLineState :: s -> CmdLineP s ()
#      Used by GHC to mutate the `DynFlags` record as flags are
#      parsed (`-fwarn-orphans` sets a bit in DynFlags, etc.).
#      Compare:
#        clap (Rust):      derive-based struct mutation
#        cobra (Go):       direct struct-field assignment via pointer
#        GHC CmdLineParser: STATE-MONAD-BASED — pure functional
#                          state transformation through the parse.
#      Idiomatic Haskell — the parser is pure, state changes are
#      explicit via monad bind.
#
#   6. `processArgs` ENTRY POINT — the canonical entry that drives
#      the parser:
#         processArgs :: Monad m
#                     => [Flag m]                  -- defined flags
#                     -> [Located String]          -- argv as Located
#                     -> m ( [Located String]      -- leftover argv
#                          , [Located String]      -- errors
#                          , [Located String]      -- warnings
#                          )
#      The `Located` wrapper attaches a source-location (`SrcLoc`) to
#      each string for error reporting (e.g. "error in --foo at
#      command-line position 3").  Compare:
#        argparse:     `parser.parse_args()` no source-location info
#        clap:         `Args::parse()` no source-location info
#        GHC CmdLineParser: SOURCE-LOCATED parsing — every argv element
#                          carries its position for diagnostic-quality
#                          error messages.
#
#   7. INTEGRATION WITH HASKELL'S MODULE / IMPORT SYSTEM — Eta /GHC's
#      flag set INCLUDES flags that REGISTER MODULES (`-package`,
#      `-hide-package`), MUTATE THE PACKAGE DATABASE (`-package-db`),
#      ADD COMPILER PLUGINS (`-fplugin`), and modify import paths
#      (`-i` adds source-search-path).  These flags interact deeply
#      with the Haskell type-checker and module loader — making the
#      CmdLineParser TIGHTLY COUPLED to GHC's compilation pipeline,
#      unlike standalone CLI libraries that just produce values for
#      downstream code to use.  No other documented CLI library has
#      this depth of compiler-internal integration.
#
# THE Eta.Main.CmdLineParser API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream)
#
#   module Eta.Main.CmdLineParser
#       ( processArgs
#       , OptKind(..)
#       , GhcFlagMode(..)
#       , CmdLineP(..), getCmdLineState, putCmdLineState
#       , Flag(..), defFlag, defGhcFlag, defGhciFlag, defHiddenFlag
#       , errorsToGhcException
#       , EwM, runEwM
#       , addErr, addWarn, getArg, getCurLoc, liftEwM, deprecate
#       ) where
#
# Eta inherits this verbatim from GHC and uses it to define ~500+
# compiler flags across:
#   - Language extensions  (-XScopedTypeVariables, -XGADTs, etc.)
#   - Warnings             (-Wall, -Wno-orphans, -Werror, etc.)
#   - Optimization passes  (-O, -O0, -O1, -O2, -fenable-rewrite-rules)
#   - Target settings      (--make, -c, --interactive)
#   - JVM-specific flags   (-target-language=java, -dump-jvm, etc.
#                            — Eta extensions to GHC)
#   - Diagnostics          (-v, -ddump-parsed, -ddump-rn, ...)
#   - Package management   (-package, -hide-package, -package-db)
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER LANGUAGE-COMPILER CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN
# THE CORPUS:
#
#   * Wren (wren_cli)             — bare strcmp() ad-hoc parser
#   * Squirrel (sq)               — switch-on-argv[1][1] C parser
#   * Pawn (pawncc) R509          — Borland-Turbo-C-style attached-
#                                    value parser
#   * Virgil (v3c) R501           — generic Option<T> with handler
#                                    closures in Virgil stdlib
#   * Nemerle (nemish) R505       — variant CliOption with per-
#                                    constructor handler in
#                                    Nemerle.Utility.Getopt (9 variants)
#   * Frege (fregec)              — Haskell-style monadic pattern-
#                                    matching argv parser in Frege
#                                    stdlib
#   * Cone (conec) R517           — POSIX-getopt-style table-driven
#                                    static C `opt_arg_t args[]`
#   * Eta (eta, THIS)             — GHC CmdLineParser inherited from
#                                    Glasgow Haskell Compiler — 12-
#                                    constructor OptKind sum type +
#                                    EwM errors-and-warnings monad +
#                                    four-tier GhcFlagMode scoping +
#                                    three-pass static/mode/dynamic
#                                    parsing + CmdLineP state monad +
#                                    SourceLoc-attached argv for
#                                    diagnostic-quality errors +
#                                    tight integration with Haskell
#                                    package database + plugin system.
#
# Eta occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **MOST SOPHISTICATED LANGUAGE-
# COMPILER CLI LIBRARY** documented in the taxonomy.  Where Pawn,
# Wren, and Squirrel use ad-hoc switch-on-argv parsers, and Virgil,
# Nemerle, Frege, Cone use mid-complexity algebraic option types,
# **GHC's CmdLineParser (inherited by Eta) represents the upper bound
# of CLI-library sophistication** — designed to handle GHC's ~500+
# flag surface spanning language semantics, optimization passes,
# warning controls, target codegen, and package management.
#
# Eta inherits this entire library "for free" by virtue of being a
# hard fork of GHC.
#
# REAL-WORLD eta USERS (historically, before TypeLead pivoted):
#
#   * Various TypeLead client engagements in finance / fintech
#       (2017-2020) using Eta as the Haskell-on-JVM compilation
#       target for production Haskell code that needed JVM
#       interop
#   * Academic research projects exploring Haskell's adaptability
#       to non-LLVM targets
#   * The eta-* npm-style package ecosystem on etlas (Eta's build
#       tool — sister project to Cabal/Stack for Eta)
#   * Migration paths for legacy JVM systems that wanted Haskell-
#       style type safety without losing JVM library access
#
# Eta is currently in an ARCHIVED state — TypeLead's pivot to
# commercial offerings ~2020 left the open-source compiler without
# active maintainership, but the source remains available and
# functional for educational / research use.
#
# ETA LANGUAGE TIES TO OTHER LANGUAGES IN THE TAXONOMY:
#
#   * Haskell — Eta is a hard fork of GHC 7.10.3, inherits GHC's
#       entire Haskell 2010 + extensions surface
#   * Frege — fellow Haskell-on-JVM language (active alternative);
#       Frege is academically-aimed where Eta was commercial-aimed
#   * Scala — JVM functional language alternative
#   * Kotlin — pragmatic JVM language alternative
#   * Java — Eta's FFI interop target
#   * GHC — Eta inherits GHC's CmdLineParser CLI library wholesale
#   * etlas (Eta's Cabal fork) — Eta-specific build tool, sister to
#       Cabal/Stack for Haskell
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ETA'S CLI SURFACE (subset of ~500+ flags inherited from GHC)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   eta [OPTIONS] <source.hs ...>
#   eta --interactive       Drop into eta REPL
#   eta --make Main.hs      Build Main.hs and dependencies
#
# Mode flags (parsed in Phase 2 of three-pass):
#   --make                       Compile in batch mode (default for .hs)
#   --interactive, -e            Interactive REPL (eta repl)
#   -c                           Compile only (don't link)
#   -E                           Run preprocessor only
#   --help                       Show help
#   --version                    Show version
#   --print-libdir               Print Eta's libdir
#   --print-package-name         Print package name
#   -M, --dependency             Generate dependency information
#
# Language extension flags (hundreds — see GHC user guide):
#   -XScopedTypeVariables        Enable ScopedTypeVariables
#   -XGADTs                      Enable GADTs
#   -XTypeFamilies               Enable type families
#   -XOverloadedStrings          Enable overloaded strings
#   -XRankNTypes                 Enable rank-N types
#   ... (~150 -X language extensions)
#
# Warning flags:
#   -Wall                        Enable all warnings
#   -Wno-orphans                 Disable orphans warning
#   -Werror                      Treat warnings as errors
#   -Wcompat                     Enable compatibility warnings
#   ... (~50 warning flags)
#
# Optimization flags:
#   -O0                          No optimization
#   -O, -O1                      Default optimization
#   -O2                          Maximum optimization
#   -funfolding-use-threshold=N  Inline-decision threshold
#   -fmax-inline-rhs-size=N      Max inline RHS size
#   ... (~30 -f optimization flags)
#
# Eta-specific JVM target flags (beyond GHC):
#   --target-language=java       Generate Java sources (debug only)
#   -ddump-jvm                   Dump JVM bytecode
#   -clean                       Clean before build
#
# Package management:
#   -package <PKG>               Use specific package
#   -hide-package <PKG>          Hide a package
#   -package-db <DB>             Add a package database
#   -i<DIR>                      Add source-search directory
#
# Diagnostic / debug:
#   -v, -vN                      Verbosity level (0-4)
#   -ddump-parsed                Dump parsed AST
#   -ddump-rn                    Dump renamed code
#   -ddump-tc                    Dump type-checked code
#   -ddump-ds                    Dump desugared core
#   -ddump-stg                   Dump STG
#   -ddump-jvm                   Dump JVM bytecode
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ eta Main.hs                          # Compile Main.hs to .class
#   $ eta --make Main.hs                   # Compile + link
#   $ eta -O2 -Wall Main.hs                # Optimized + all warnings
#   $ eta --interactive                    # REPL
#   $ eta -package text-1.2.5.0 Main.hs    # Use specific package
#   $ eta -XGADTs -XTypeFamilies Main.hs   # Enable extensions
#   $ eta -ddump-parsed Main.hs            # Dump parsed AST
#
# Companion tools:
#   etlas                        Eta's build tool (sister to Cabal/Stack)
#                                 — uses Eta CmdLineParser for its own
#                                 flag parsing
#   eta-pkg                      Eta package database management
#
# =============================================================================

_eta() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    # Eta's flag surface is ~500+ flags inherited from GHC.  We complete
    # the most common subset; rare GHC flags are accepted but not
    # explicitly listed.
    _arguments -C \
        '--make[compile in batch mode]' \
        '(-e --interactive)'{-e,--interactive}'[drop into eta REPL]' \
        '-c[compile only, do not link]' \
        '-E[run preprocessor only]' \
        '(- *)--help[show help]' \
        '(- *)--version[show version]' \
        '--print-libdir[print Eta libdir]' \
        '--print-package-name[print package name]' \
        '(-M --dependency)'{-M,--dependency}'[generate dependency info]' \
        '-O0[no optimization]' \
        '-O[default optimization]' \
        '-O1[level 1 optimization]' \
        '-O2[maximum optimization]' \
        '-Wall[enable all warnings]' \
        '-Wcompat[enable compatibility warnings]' \
        '-Werror[treat warnings as errors]' \
        '-Wno-*[disable specific warning]' \
        '-XScopedTypeVariables[enable ScopedTypeVariables]' \
        '-XGADTs[enable GADTs]' \
        '-XTypeFamilies[enable type families]' \
        '-XOverloadedStrings[enable overloaded strings]' \
        '-XRankNTypes[enable rank-N types]' \
        '-XMultiParamTypeClasses[enable multi-parameter type classes]' \
        '-XFlexibleContexts[enable flexible contexts]' \
        '-XFlexibleInstances[enable flexible instances]' \
        '-XDeriveGeneric[enable DeriveGeneric]' \
        '-XLambdaCase[enable lambda case]' \
        '-XViewPatterns[enable view patterns]' \
        '-XDataKinds[enable DataKinds]' \
        '-XPolyKinds[enable PolyKinds]' \
        '-X*[language extension]' \
        '-f*[GHC fine-grained flag]' \
        '-d*[GHC dump/debug flag]' \
        '-package[use specific package]:package:' \
        '-hide-package[hide a package]:package:' \
        '-package-db[add a package database]:db:_files -g "*.conf*"' \
        '-i-[add source-search directory]:dir:_directories' \
        '-o[output file]:file:_files' \
        '-odir[output dir for .class]:dir:_directories' \
        '-hidir[output dir for .hi]:dir:_directories' \
        '-stubdir[output dir for stubs]:dir:_directories' \
        '-v[verbose]' \
        '-v0[silent verbosity]' \
        '-v1[basic verbosity]' \
        '-v2[detailed verbosity]' \
        '-v3[very verbose]' \
        '-v4[maximum verbosity]' \
        '--target-language=-[generate sources for specific JVM language]:lang:(java)' \
        '-ddump-parsed[dump parsed AST]' \
        '-ddump-rn[dump renamed code]' \
        '-ddump-tc[dump type-checked code]' \
        '-ddump-ds[dump desugared core]' \
        '-ddump-stg[dump STG]' \
        '-ddump-jvm[dump JVM bytecode]' \
        '-clean[clean before build]' \
        '*:haskell source file:_files -g "*.(hs|lhs|hsc)"' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_eta "$@"
